    "html": "<section class=\"problem\" id=\"Continuous-and-Discrete-Graphs\"><h2>Continuous and Discrete Graphs</h2><div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 8, Section 1: Function Analysis and Modeling</div><div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Summarizes when graphs should be continuous or discrete and connects that decision to context.</div><div class=\"contentContainerReference-body\"><p class=\"\" style=\"\"></p><h2 style=\"\">Continuous and Discrete Graphs</h2><p class=\"\" style=\"\">When the points on a graph are connected, and it <em>makes sense</em> to connect them, the graph is said to be <span class=\"glossary-link\" data-glossary-item-id=\"369ad2b0-7343-11e9-be9b-611c324990be\">continuous</span>. If the graph is not continuous, and is just a sequence of separate points, the graph is called <span class=\"glossary-link\" data-glossary-item-id=\"cb8de2a0-7342-11e9-be9b-611c324990be\">discrete</span>. For example, the graph below left represents the cost of buying <em>$x$</em> shirts, and it is discrete because you can only buy whole numbers of shirts. The graph below farthest right represents the cost of buying <em>$x$</em> gallons of gasoline, and it is continuous because you can buy any (non-negative) amount of gasoline.</p><p class=\"\" style=\"text-align: center\"></p></div></section>",
