    "html": "<section class=\"problem\" id=\"5-119\">\n<h2>5-119</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Review/Preview</span> Sorted to Unit 8, Section 1: Selecting Appropriate Models</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Compares arithmetic, geometric, and custom sequence models that begin with the same initial values.</div>\n<div><p>Consider the following sequences as you complete parts (a) through (c) below.  </p><div class=\"row\"><div class=\"col-sm-4\"><p><strong>Sequence 1</strong><br/> $2$, $6$, … </p></div><div class=\"col-sm-4\"><p><strong>Sequence 2</strong><br/> $24$, $12$, … </p></div><div class=\"col-sm-4\"><p><strong>Sequence 3</strong><br/> $1$, $5$, … </p></div></div><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>Assuming that the sequences above are arithmetic with <em>$t(1)$</em> as the first term, find the next four terms for each sequence. For each sequence, write an explanation of what you did to get the next term and write an equation for <em>$t(n)$</em>.</p></li><li><p>Would your terms be different if the sequences were geometric? Find the next four terms for each sequence if they are geometric. For each sequence, write an explanation of what you did to get the next term and write an equation for <em>$t(n)$</em>.</p></li><li><p>Create a totally different type of sequence for each pair of values shown above, based on your own equation. Write your equation clearly (using words or algebra) so that someone else will be able to find the next three terms that you want.</p></li></ol></div>\n</section>",
