    "html": "<section class=\"problem\" id=\"6-105\">\n<h2>6-105</h2>\n<div class=\"tagline\"><span class=\"pill\">Lesson</span> Sorted to Unit 8, Section 1: Selecting Appropriate Models</div>\n<div class=\"audit\">Audit note: Uses scatterplot, LSRL, residual plot, correlation, and R-squared to question whether a linear model fits curved data.</div>\n<div><div><div class=\"row\"><div class=\"col-sm-9\"><p>Top-It-Off Incorporated makes numerous lids for a variety of containers. Some of the most popular lids they produce are circular lids for oil drums and other cylindrical containers. Although the lids are ordered by the diameter of the circle, the price is set by the amount of metal used. Top-It-Off needs to set up a price structure that relates the weight of a lid to its diameter. Below is a list of weights for the standard size lids currently produced. </p></div><div class=\"col-sm-3 col-align-top\"><p><strong></strong></p></div></div><table><tbody><tr><th><p>Diameter of lid (in)</p></th><th><p>Weight of metal (lbs)</p></th></tr><tr><td><p>$10$</p></td><td><p>$3.9$</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>$12$</p></td><td><p>$5.7$</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>$16$</p></td><td><p>$10.1$</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>$20$</p></td><td><p>$15.7$</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>$24$</p></td><td><p>$22.6$</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>$30$</p></td><td><p>$35.3$</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>$36$</p></td><td><p>$50.9$</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>$40$</p></td><td><p>$62.8$</p></td></tr></tbody></table><ol class=\"lower-alpha\" type=\"a\"><li><p>The company analyst needs to find a good model for the weight as a function of the diameter. Use your calculator or <a class=\"etool-link\" href=\"https://www.desmos.com/calculator/b7wgeky9o8\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">6-105 Student eTool</a> to create a scatterplot of your data and sketch the results.<strong> </strong>Click in the lower right corner of the graph to view it in full-screen mode.   \t\t</p></li><li><p>The data appears to have only a slight curve. Based on the scatterplot alone, you may think a linear model would be a good fit. Use your calculator to find the equation of the LSRL. Add this line to the sketch from part (a). </p></li><li><p>Make a residual plot for your model. What conclusion can you draw about your linear model? </p></li><li><p>What is the correlation coefficient? Write a sentence about <em>$R$</em>-squared in context.  </p></li></ol></div><p><img alt=\"Figure for 6-105\" class=\"figure-img\" src=\"assets/6-105.png\"/></p></div>\n</section>",
